[2] Bulgaria
Date: 12 Nov 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EU Health & Consumer Protection DG web-site [edited]
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/bluetongue_bulgaria08112006.pdf>

The epidemiological BT situation in Bulgaria as of 8 Nov 2006
-----------------------------------------------
The epidemiological BT situation in Bulgaria as of 8 Nov 2006 is favorable,
no clinical BT signs were revealed at the clinical examinations performed
on sheep in the municipalities of Burgas Region.
All serological tests of blood samples from cattle and goats taken for
routine testing under the 2006 BT Surveillance testing Program showed
negative results, except those ruminants originating from the border
villages of the municipality of Malko Tarnovo and Tsharevo, Region Burgas
(taken in all municipalities near the southern and western borders of the
country).
November weather forecast and expectations:
- On 3 Nov 2006, a cold air stream appeared on the territory of Bulgaria,
and the 1st snow fell;
- Temperatures drop in the country - 0 [below 0 C?];
- Retention of the low temperatures during the next week.
- No insects were caught by the light traps during the last week.
Additional activity:
152 additional blood tests (to those from the monitoring program) taken
from 14 villages situated within a 10-km zone far from the villages with
the seropositive cases;
Five new villages with seropositive cases in cattle and goats sampled on 5
Nov 2006 (table in slide 7):
1. 35 head of cattle, from 14 settlements; positive serology obtained in 2
cows from one settlement (Velika).
2. 118 goats in 13 settlements (the same as the above, but Velika not
included); positive serology obtained in 9 goats from 4 settlements:
Ahtopol (3/10); Tsarevo (1/20); Granichar (3/8); Belevren (2/10).
Ten blood samples with EDTA taken from serological positive cows for
virological examination;
Four samples for BT virus typing sent to the EU Reference laboratory for
Bluetongue, Pirbright.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Four separate BTV cycles seem to be currently evolving in Europe: one in
the north caused by BTV-8, affecting cattle and sheep; a mid-southern one
(Sardinia) caused by BTV-1, affecting sheep; and -- reportedly, and
probably without noticeable clinical manifestation -- 2 other cycles, one
in the southeast (Bulgaria), the other one in the southwest (Portugal), as
described in the above text derived from their respective presentations in
Brussels. The BTV serotype(s) involved in their current Bulgarian and
Portuguese cycles have not yet been identified or reported. Previous BT
outbreaks in Bulgaria were caused by BTV-9 (1999); in 2002, sentinel goats
were found seropositive) and in Portugal by BTV-4 (2004-2005).
An updated (10 Nov 2006) map of the epizootic in Belgium, France, Germany
and the Netherlands is available at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/pdf/bt-europemap.pdf>.
- Mod.AS]
